'''''Galaxy of Fear: Clones''''' is the eleventh book in the young readers ''[[Star Wars: Galaxy of Fear]]'' series.

==Publisher's summary==
''In the Ruins of an abandoned Jedi Fortress on the remote planet Dantooine, Tash Arranda stands, all alone. At least, she thinks she's alone. She senses something in the ruins — Something Dark.''

''The darkness is stronger than Tash, and Against her will, she reaches out to it. It makes her feel powerful. And it frightens her. Tash doesn't know that this is only the beginning of a terrifying journey into an evil world, where she'll be forced to fight her own brother and uncle .... to the death!''

==Plot summary==
A visit to [[Dantooine/Legends|Dantooine]] causes [[Tash Arranda/Legends|Tash]] to reflect upon her [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force sensitivity]] and fret about her tendency to embrace anger and the [[Dark side of the Force/Legends|dark side]]. The Arrandas and [[Mammon Hoole|Hoole]] make a bizarre discovery amid some ancient [[Jedi Enclave|Jedi ruins]] – an entire camp of [[Cloning/Legends|cloned]] [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebels]] living in the remains of a [[Dantooine base/Legends|Rebel base]] led by a [[Darth Vader (clone)|clone of Darth Vader]]. The ancient Jedi ruins conceal advanced cloning technology that can rapidly duplicate people, and Tash, [[Zak Arranda/Legends|Zak]], and Hoole all must face copies of one another before they scape the [[Dream/Legends|nightmarish]] scenario, aided by the [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|real Darth Vader]] who [[Death/Legends|destroys]] his own doppelgänger. Though the trio escaped, they have once again raised the ire of Vader.

==Continuity==
One of the toughest stories to reconcile with ongoing continuity, ''Clones'' introduced an extremely advanced form of [[Cloning/Legends|cloning]] that outpaced all others depicted elsewhere. The [[Jedi Enclave|ruins of Dantooine]] were shown in active use in the [[Star Wars: Tales of the Jedi (comic series)|''Tales of the Jedi'']] and [[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic (comic series)|''Knights of the Old Republic'']] comics, but there were no indication of any cloning technology in use during that era. [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Vader]] captured the cloning tech for the [[Palpatine/Legends|Emperor]] by the end of ''Clones'', but it never surfaced again. Also unanswered is why a clone of Vader would resemble a [[Gender/Legends|man]] who was mostly [[Cyborg/Legends|artificial]].<ref name="TERC" />

